    <description>
     <narrative xml:lang="EN">Number of businesses in the plastic waste recovery value chain provided with financial and technical support through the Waste Recovery Innovation Challenge (WRIC) competition to test, pilot and demonstrate solutions for plastic waste management 
Number of firm engaged to provide technical and business support services to winners of the Waste Recovery Innovation Challenge</narrative>
    </description>
    <baseline year="2020">
     <comment>
      <narrative xml:lang="EN">0 Number of businesses in the plastic waste recovery value chain provided with financial and technical support through the Waste Recovery Innovation Challenge (WRIC) competition to test, pilot and demonstrate solutions for plastic waste management 
0 Number of firm engaged to provide technical and business support services to winners of the Waste Recovery Innovation Challenge</narrative>
     </comment>
    </baseline>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2020-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2020-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">3 businesses in the plastic waste recovery value chain provided with financial and technical support through the Waste Recovery Innovation Challenge (WRIC) competition to test, pilot and demonstrate solutions for plastic waste management 
1 firm engaged to provide technical and business support services to winners of the Waste Recovery Innovation Challenge</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">Four (4) innovators/businesses namely Mckingtorch Africa, SESA Recycling Limited, Pyramid Recycling Enterprise, and City Waste Recycling were awarded cash grants totaling about $130,000 to implement solutions for plastic waste recovery ranging from recycling of plastic waste bags and pure water sachet bags mainly into leather which is used as raw material for production of slippers and sandals, implementing a reward-for-recycling scheme to motivate consumers to segregate and recycle water sachet, plastic bottles, hard plastics and beverage cans. The other innovations are using all forms of plastic waste to produce valuable household items like curtain ropes, chair shoes and wood plastic composite for building and innovator that collects, segregates, and recycles plastic waste into products like cosmetic containers, sanitizer bottles and irrigation cans for farmers. In total, these innovators/businesses have recycled 1355.5 tons of plastic waste so far, provided 59 (40 females, 19 males) direct and 173 (122 females, 51 males) indirect jobs to people along the plastic waste value chain. 15 new business networks were established by the innovators with various institutions including research and academia, other businesses and incubator laps, local government authorities, among others. Revenue generated by all four innovators as at the time of reporting is GHS 409,166.8, equivalent of about $70,000. The innovators had attracted an additional investment with 5 entities. 

1 firm (Ernst and Young, EY) provided business service solution to the companies by investigating factors and opportunities for growth with the companies and developed action plan with the companies to mitigate the factors and leverage the opportunities.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2021-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2021-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">No target set for this year as all activities related to this output was expected to be completed in 2020. However monitoring of the results spill over into 2021 and 2022 to assess the impact of the intervention.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">No result for this year, as output related actions were exhausted in 2020, however the results of the impact of the intervention through monitoring is being documented.</narrative>
      </comment>
     </actual>
    </period>
